    When a child process is created, it may share resources such as open files, environment variables, and program code with the parent process. However, it has its own PID, PCB, memory space, CPU registers, and execution state, making it an independent process.

    1. Resources Shared Between Parent and Child Process
        These resources may be shared or inherited by the child process.
        1. Open Files
            . Child process inherits open file descriptors from the parent.
            . Both processes can access the same file.
        2. Environment Variables
            The child process receives a copy of the parent’s environment variables.
        3. Program Code (Initially)
            . Parent and child may share the same program code in memory initially.
            . Many systems use Copy-on-Write (COW) to optimize memory usage.
        4. Shared Libraries
            Both processes may use the same shared libraries loaded in memory.
        5. Some System Resources
            Current working directory, Signal handlers, File permissions
